Case-sensitivity bug: protected columns (PK and incremental field) are not normalized before being checked against masked columns. If `masked_columns` contains `"ID"` and `primary_key_columns` contains `"id"`, the protection logic fails and the PK gets masked, corrupting merges.

```python
# Fix: normalize protected column names
protected: set[str] = set()
for pk in self.pk_columns_by_table.get(schema.name, []):
    try:
        protected.add(NamingConvention.normalize_identifier(pk))
    except ValueError:
        protected.add(pk)
masked_inc = schema.incremental_field
if isinstance(masked_inc, str) and masked_inc:
    try:
        protected.add(NamingConvention.normalize_identifier(masked_inc))
    except ValueError:
        protected.add(masked_inc)
self.masked_columns_by_table[schema.name] = {
    NamingConvention.normalize_identifier(str(c)) if isinstance(c, str) else str(c)
    for c in masked
} - protected
```

The same normalization logic used in `resolve_masked_columns()` (lines 46-49 in masking.py) must be applied here to ensure case-insensitive matching.
